We recommend the Municipal Mayor to:

a. Instruct the Inventory Committee to ensure the conduct the complete or full inventory taking of PPE items and prepare and submit afterwards; 

b. Instruct the No Member - Inventory, Appraisal and Disposal Committee and the Accounting Unit to perform the preliminary activities of the AAPSI and reconcile their records thereof; 

c. Plan/strategize on how the reported Municipality would apply the one-time cleansing and incorporate it in the PIP to be submitted at least 10 calendar days before the scheduled inventory-taking activities; and

d. Immediately start the application of the One-time cleansing of the PPEs.

We recommended that:

a. The Municipal Accountant to maintain a record of each land by using the Real Property Ledger Card, which shall include a complete description of the lot as to area, title number, tax declaration number, PIN, location and other applicable data;

b. The GSO to maintain Property Cards for each land owned by the Municipality containing details such as land area, title number, tax declaration number, PIN, location, actual utilization of such lot, specific improvements or buildings erected in the lot and other applicable data of each lot; 

c. The MGSO to coordinate with the Assessor’s Office for the conduct of physical count of land to determine the actual location of the lot; and

d. The Municipal Accountant and MGSO to follow the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of land, recognition of land items found at station and the disposition of non-existing/missing land items stated in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 for the One-Time-Cleansing of PPE account balances.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accountant to:
a. Make proper adjustment for the recognition of stale check no. 840237 in the Cash in Bank – Local Currency, Current Account amounting to P7,303.80 and submit copy thereof to the Audit Team for verification. Henceforth, strictly observe the policies on the recognition of stale checks as prescribed in the Section 59 and 61 of the Manual on NGAS Volume 1;
b. For the subsequent unreleased checks as of year-end, ensure that adjusting entry will be made to restore the balance of Cash in Bank – Local Currency, Current Account and set up its appropriate payable accounts;
c. Review the noted observations regarding depreciation and effect the necessary adjustments. Submit copies of the adjusting journal entries made to the audit team. Henceforth, strictly observe the policies on the recognition of depreciation for PPE prescribed in PAG 3 of IPSAS 17 and Section 14 of COA Circular No. 2015-008;
d. Municipal Accountant to review the composition of the Due to NGAs account and prepare the necessary adjusting entries, if warranted, furnishing the Audit Team with the copies thereof for further evaluation;
e. Submit to the Audit Team the revised General Ledger of Office Supplies Expenses and Donations; and
f. Submit to the Audit Team the lacking Subsidiary Ledgers of those accounts noted in this audit finding and ensure the maintenance of individual SLs to support the corresponding GL control account.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
a. Municipal Accountant and the Acting Municipal General Services Officer (MGSO) to reconcile their respective records and consider the inclusion of the PPE items’ specifications for proper identification;
b. Municipal Accountant to provide depreciation for PPE costing P14,748,921.45 for a fairly presented balance in the financial statements and submit to the COA Audit Team the Journal Entry Voucher for the adjustments made;
c. Inventory Committee to adopt the procedural guidelines under COA Circular No. 2020-006 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances; and
d. Municipal Administrator to submit to the COA Audit Team the Action Plan of Management for the implementation of this audit recommendations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct:
a. The Inventory Committee, immediately after conduct of complete physical count, reconcile inventory results with property and accounting records;
b. The Property and Accounting units to perform reconciliation of the PPE balance particularly on the noted difference of P5,232,843.77 and make the necessary adjustments/recording of entries, if any;
c. The Inventory Committee to ensure that all counted items are properly specified and identified detailing physical attributes and location;
d. The Municipal Accountant disclose in the Notes to the Financial Statements the results of reconciliation of RPCPPE and accounting records as well as the amount of PPE items, if any, without available supporting documents; and
e. The existing Inventory Committee or a newly created Inventory Committee study the provisions of COA Circular 2020-006 on one-time cleansing of PPE and consider its implementation to account for the non-existing PPEs and to present reliable balances in the financial statements.

