We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct:
a. The Municipal Assessor to declare for tax assessment purposes the noted lots without Tax Declarations and to provide the Municipal Accounting Office and Municipal General Services Office complete and necessary information of the land owned by the Municipality; 
b. The Municipal Accountant to take up necessary accounting entries to recognize unrecorded lots after the conduct of comprehensive reconciliation of lands owned by the Municipality; 
c. The Municipal Accountant to maintain a record of each land by using the Real Property Ledger Card, which shall include a complete description of the lot as to area, title number, tax declaration number, PIN, location and other applicable data; 
d. The Municipal General Services Officer to maintain Property Cards for each land owned by the Municipality containing details such as land area, title number, tax declaration number, PIN, location, actual utilization of such lot, specific improvements or buildings erected in the lot and other applicable data of each lot; 
e. The GSO to coordinate with the Municipal Assessor’s Office for the conduct of physical count of land to determine the actual location of the lot; and 
f. The Municipal Accountant and Municipal GSO to follow the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of land, recognition of land items found at station and disposition of non-existing/missing land items stated in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE account balances.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to:
a. Instruct the Inventory Committee, the designated GSO and the Accounting Office to strictly follow the general guidelines, appointing and reorganizing the Inventory/Valuation/Disposal Committee who shall be responsible for its conduct of actual physical count of all properties, determination and assignment of permanent property number and determination of disposable properties; 
b. Require the OIC Municipal Accountant to make detailed evaluation and tracing of the noted unaccounted beginning balances to reflect the reliable balances of these accounts in the Financial Statements; 
c. Instruct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer with the complete description and cost segregation of road component for road projects; 
d. Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain the prescribed Property Ledger Card for Local Road Network; 
e. Municipal Treasurer to periodically maintain a complete Report on Local Road Network, prepare the Road Map and keep complete Local Road Network Property Cards for all roads and their components and furnish copies; and 
f. Inventory Committee in coordination with the Municipal Engineering Office to (i) conduct physical inventory of all existing local road networks in the municipality and prepare the corresponding Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network to be reconciled with the accounting records and (ii) furnish a copy of such report to the Audit Team for verification and audit.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. Instruct the Inventory Committee to properly utilize the required inventory reports stated on the above-mentioned regulations; 
b. Require the Municipal Accountant and the GSO-Designate to work coordinately with the assistance of the Municipal Engineer on the inventory of Infrastructure Assets such as Land Improvements, Local Road Network, Flood Control System and Other Public Infrastructure and to exert efforts on all causes of discrepancies towards the needed reconciliation of their respective records to ascertain the accuracy of the PPE balances in the financial statements; 
c. Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to periodically maintain a complete Report on Local Road Network and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Cards for all roads and their components and furnish copies thereof to the concerned offices; 
d. Instruct the Inventory Committee in coordination with the Municipal Engineering Office to conduct physical inventory of all existing local road networks in the Municipality and prepare the corresponding Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network to be reconciled with the accounting records and furnish a copy to the Audit Team for verification and audit; and 
e. Take steps to adopt and initiate the guidelines and procedures for one-time cleansing of PPE as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a. Municipal Accountant to: • prepare and maintain the Local Road Network Ledger Card for the road and its component namely: a) road lot, b) road pavement, c) drainage and slope protection structures and d) other miscellaneous structures; and • disclose the total road network system in the Notes to Financial Statements;
b. designated GSO to: • prepare and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network and Report on the Local Road Network in the prescribed format; and • maintain a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its component;
c. Municipal Engineer to prepare the complete description and cost segregation of road components of every road project undertaken; and
d. Municipal Accountant and designated GSO to secure from the Municipal Engineer the complete description and cost segregation of road components of every road project undertaken to have a basis in recording the road networks in the Local Road Network Ledger Card and Local Road Network Property Card, respectively.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
a. Municipal Accountant to establish the correct amount of the Cash in Bank of the LEE - Market with abnormal/negative balance of P8,915,735.34 as of December 31, 2022, and submit to the COA Audit Team the action taken thereon;
b. Municipal Accountant to prepare the BRS for the six cash in bank accounts of the Municipality and submit to the COA Audit Team. For succeeding months, the Municipal Accountant to consistently cause the preparation and submission of the BRS for all the cash in bank accounts of the Municipality; 
c. Municipal Treasurer to prepare the complete lists of unreleased checks every year-end and submit all to the Municipal Accountant, in time for the closing of the books of account. Both the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer, to restore to the Cash in Bank and appropriate liability accounts, in their respective records, the amount corresponding to the unreleased checks at year-end; and
d. Municipal Treasurer to prepare and keep an updated cashbook for the four bank accounts, considering the complete and timely recording of all cash transactions in the cashbooks, and submit to COA Audit Team all the lacking cashbooks for evaluation.

