We reiterated our recommendations that the City Mayor direct the:
a. Inventory Committee and City Accounting Office to exhaust all efforts in the determination of the particulars, whereabouts, their custody and any documents or information pertaining to the unreconciled/ unaccounted properties of accounting records. Several reconciling items have been identified totaling to P312,845,140.22 so that eventual elimination of these unidentified properties could be achieved in the coming years, preferably sooner than later so as to reflect fair balances of PPE accounts. If necessary, require the submission from persons in charge of the PPE items of all the procedures adopted by them in the reconciliation process in order to document the process and move forward to the next course of action;
b. City Accounting Office to assign one or two personnel in her Office who will focus only on the evaluation and analysis of all properties already auctioned or disposed of, which totalled to P123,249,499.83 as found by the Inventory Committee of the GSO and effect adjustments, if found accurate and correct, in the books of accounts so as to eliminate the presence of these kind of properties;
c. City Engineering Office to submit the required documentation in support to the demolished properties of P11,348,775.14 to the IC-GSO and the City Accounting Office for them to effect appropriate action thereof;
d. City Engineer to submit to the Audit Team all necessary documents and information pertaining to the demolished properties, pursuant to PD No. 1096 and its IRR, and RA No. 7160 so that corresponding analysis of these documents could be made to determine the City’s compliance with the proper procedures on property disposal, and for transparency and proper accountability of such undertaking; and
e. Inventory Committee and City Accounting Office to submit to COA the updates/ development of the reconciliation of their records every semester for verification and monitoring purposes.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the concerned City officials to:
a) Submit the detailed Basis of the computation, breakdown of the ABC showing in sufficient details the derivation; the measurement in kilometres of the total distance covered by one complete routes to be travelled; and estimated volume in cubic meters of garbage to be hauled from area of operation, including the basis for such estimates used in the breakdown of the contract amount so as to determine the reasonableness of the contract price P57,716,362.82;
b) Furnish the Audit Team of all the required but lacking supporting documents and the necessary explanation for the deficiencies noted to substantiate the payments made. Strict compliance with the procedures and documentary requirements for common government transactions as prescribed in the afore-cited laws, rules and regulations should be adopted so as to ensure that all contracts entered into by the City is valid and legal;
c) Comply strictly with the proper procedures in the preparation, submission and approval of PPMP and APP so as to ensure that procurement of programs or projects are in accordance with the provisions of Section 17 of RA No. 9184;
d) Submit explanation/justification on why penalties imposed against the Metrowaste for the unsatisfactory rating given by CENRO for the maintenance of sanitary landfill for July and October 2017 were not deducted from the payment to the said service provider. Otherwise, collection of the amount of  
(e) Process, approve and pay claims only with complete documentation to protect the interest of the City.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct concerned officials to:
a) require the service provider to justify the deficiency of 902 short trips which is equivalent to P£3,341,034.37, otherwise, refund the amount in favor of the government; 
b) ensure that the service provider for garbage collection and disposal services fully comply in executing the daily minimum requirement of trips; 
c) prepare and issue appropriate serially numbered trip tickets to countercheck the service provider's self issued trip tickets. Assigned a responsible person who will monitor the actual number of trips per day and capacity load of each truck; and
d) revisit the contract and amend the terms of payment to include the actual number of trips conducted per month at a full load capacity as basis for payments.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the concerned officials to:
a) set guidelines and criteria in the process of hiring and selection of job order workers;
b) conduct a study on the actual workload and the required number of additional manpower needed per office to establish the necessity of hiring job order workers in addition to the City's existing plantilla of personnel;
c) ensure that contracts entered into and issued to job order workers have specific job functions and implement an ID system for them; and
d) pay only those claims for wages with appropriate individual accomplishment reports.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the concerned officials to:
a) come up with a detailed Annual Investment Plan (AIP) indicating the priority programs, projects and activities (PPA) in its Barangays through consultation and deliberation with concerned Barangay officials;
b) incorporate in the AIP the complete description of the project, exact location, intended beneficiaries and estimated cost of each project;
c) monitor the implementation and ensure optimal utilization of the funds for the intended development programs and projects; and
d) make sure that only those projects in the approved AIP be implemented. Otherwise, Sangguniang Panlungsod should pass a resolution for the realignment/amendments, if any.

We recommended that the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS), through the TWG:
a) properly identify gender issues, require only the inclusion of gender sensitive and responsive programs, projects and activities and indicate well defined key performance indicator in the City’s GAD Plan and Budget (GBP) to facilitate sound evaluation and assessment. We also recommended that the LGU GFPS assess the status of the LGU’s institutional mechanism on gender mainstreaming annually;
b) prepare the GAD Accomplishment Report (GAD AR) rigidly, incorporate therein concrete and comprehensive output/outcome in the actual result column;
c) make sure to present the approved budget for each GAD activity by specific object of expenditure to come up with a reasonable budget estimate and for maximum utilization of fund; and
d) regularly monitor the implementation of GAD PPAs and its related budget to ensure that they are expended for the purpose it has been intended, assess and account the result in the GAD AR for proper monitoring, evaluation and action.
